<br />
&quot;Oh size doesn&#39;t matter.&quot;  <br />
<br />
&quot;It&#39;s not how big it is, but how well you use it.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Something that big just won&#39;t fit so I don&#39;t think about it.&quot;<br />
<br />
    I&#39;m here to tell you that these are all lies.  Some will say these things to you, but it is only to mislead you or give you a false sense of security, but I&#39;m here to set the facts straight.  <br />
<br />
   There simply is no other way around saying it,<br />
<br />
&quot;A big, long, hard, well developed Fellowship is always better than a small one.&quot;<br />
<br />
   Big Fellowships have many advantages over small ones.  When I say big, I mean Fellowships at least 7 companions large.  The more companions you have, the more vitality your opponents Shadow culture must get through to get to Frodo.  <br />
    A large, well developed Fellowship has much better staying power than a smaller one.  You, as the owner of a large Fellowship, have much more options getting your way through to the end and the final climax at site 9.<br />
    A large Fellowship is better equiped to take the plunge, thrust their way through the tight confines of Moria and come out the tunnel to relax at site 6.<br />
<br />
    The name of the game is survival.  It doesn&#39;t really matter who survives site 9 with Frodo, just so long as the little man survives himself.  Along these lines, a large Fellowship is better equiped to accompany him along his journey to victory.<br />
    Let&#39;s look at the biggest problem for small Fellowships.  Usually a small Fellowship takes a Free Peoples strategy and builds the deck around just a few companions.  An archery deck will be built around Legolas and Aragorn.  A Twilight denail deck will be built around 2 Hobbits and a couple of Rangers.  Unfortunately, if any of these companions die along the way, then the Free Peoples strategy usually dies along with them.<br />
     I prepose that a large Fellowship does not suffer from this deficiency.  Unlike a small Fellowship, a large one can easily survive the death of a few of it&#39;s members and it doesn&#39;t really matter who dies.  <br />
   The Shadow player is in a bind against a large Fellowship because they usually can not identify a key companion that must be killed.  <br />
<br />
  Another advantage for a large Fellowship is the staying power.  It is much harder for any shadow deck to kill six, seven or even eight companions during the course of the game.  I&#39;m not talking about wimpy Hobbits that are thrown to the wolves, I am talking about all the main characters from the first movie.  Aragorn, Arwen, Boromir, Gandalf, Gimli and Legolas are not very easy to get rid of and can take alot of wounds before dieing.  These 6 compaions represent 20 wounds all by themselves.  This does not take into account healing by Aragorn or healing at the sanctuaries.<br />
    Large Fellowships are also card economical.  Large Fellowships will not clutter up your hand with Strength boosting events that must wait for the right time to be played.  Instead, everything in a large Fellowship is usually deployable immediately after you draw it during your next Fellowship phase.<br />
    For instance, a large Fellowship deck would probably include doubles of everyone who was not started along with at least one copy of everyones weapon followed by a few non-unique possesions such as Armor and Athelas.  All of these could be deployed right away with the duplicate companions healing their counterparts which have been already deployed.<br />
    Large Fellowships also do not suffer from getting hosed on companion deployment.  You will not run from site 1 to site 3 or 4 with only the companions you have started with.  Since there should be about 15 copies of companions in a 60 card deck, this means companion will be available from the get go.<br />
<br />
   I know there are a few cards that specifically hurt large Fellowships, but all of these cards are easily countered with cards in the Fellowship and the one card that counters almost all of them is Intimidate.  <br />
   Savagery to Match Their Numbers is slowed by Armor (and Intimidate doesn&#39;t hurt).  Uliare Enquea is also countered by Intimidate.  This would lend a large Fellowship deck to be based, at least a little, around Gandalf, but you don&#39;t have to do this.  Let the shadow player play Enquea and try to kill of someone.  You will still have six of seven guys still around to fight and carry Frodo to safety.  <br />
   Of course, Gandalf large Fellowship decks also seem to be a good fit.  Intimidate is the bane of almost all anti-large Fellowship cards out there.  Servant of the Secret Fire is the ultimate universal STR booster for anyone in the Fellowship and I can&#39;t see myself making any deck without Sleep, Caradhras.<br />
   Large Fellowships also give away alot of pool for the shadow player to use.  I like to give my opponent as much pool as possible on turn one.  He will only have his starting 8 cards in order to draw shadow minions from and deploy.  It is much better to give them alot of pool early, before they have had time to go through a thrid of their decka nd set up enough minions in their hand.<br />
<br />
  Another strategy for large Fellowships is to deploy them slowly.  Deploy just a few guys in the beginning and simply replace fallen companions with new ones from your deck.  The look on your opponents face is priceless after they think they have killed all your companions at site 5 and then you deploy 3 more and move on to site 6.<br />
   Large Fellowships also lead into massive Fellowship healing strategies.  In this I mean all the duplicates of the companions are used to heal them along the way.  Four Athelas&#39; are also very useful to heal between sanctuaries.  Aragorn, KIE, will heal Arwen or Boromir at the beginning of each turn and rare Pippin can give that needed boost in the later sites to see your Fellowship through to the end.<br />
<br />
   Large Fellowships are the best way to go.  You may have to give up a narrow strategy, such as Twilight Denial, which could suffer from the death of one key companion, but you more than make up for it it versatility and staying power until the end.   <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=3344&view=1&PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
